<showme.pack xmlns="Compositor"
             xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
             id="Exa_VectorCoordinates"
             xsi:schemaLocation="Compositor file:/C:/xampp/htdocs/moodle2.5/mod/msm/XSLTdocuments/Compositor.xsd">
	  <texsupport href="../LinearAlgebraTeXSupport.xml"/>
	  <title>Vectors and Coordinates: Examples</title>
	  <showme>
		    <caption>Arrows representing <math>
            <latex>\Vect{x} = (3,-1)</latex>
         </math>
		    </caption>
		    <statement.showme>
			      <para>
            <para.body>The vector <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{x} = (3,-1)</latex>
               </math> is represented by any of the arrows in the picture below.</para.body>
         </para>
			      <para align="center">
            <para.body>
               <media type="image" active="0" inline="0">
                  <img src="ims/VectorCoordinates_Exmpl1.gif"/>
               </media>
            </para.body>
         </para>
		    </statement.showme>
		    <answer.showme type="Explanation">
         <answer.showme.block>
            <answer.showme.block.body>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>Indeed, consider any of these arrows. Starting from its tail, we find its tip by</para.body>
               </para>
			            <ol>
				              <li>
					                <para>
                        <para.body>moving <math>
                              <latex>3</latex>
                           </math> units in the first coordinate direction, and</para.body>
                     </para>
				              </li>
				              <li>
					                <para>
                        <para.body>from there moving <math>
                              <latex>-1</latex>
                           </math> unit in the second coordinate direction.</para.body>
                     </para>
				              </li>
			            </ol>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>For example, if we choose</para.body>
               </para>
			            <ul>
				              <li>
					                <para>
                        <para.body>
						                     <math>
                              <latex>R(2,2)</latex>
                           </math> as the tail point of an arrow representing <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                           </math>, the tip of this arrow will be at <math>
                              <latex>S(2+3,2+(-1))=S(5,1)</latex>
                           </math>
					                   </para.body>
                     </para>
				              </li>
				              <li>
					                <para>
                        <para.body>
						                     <math>
                              <latex>A(14,-6)</latex>
                           </math> as the tail point of an arrow representing <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                           </math>, the tip of this arrow will be at <math>
                              <latex>B(17,-7)</latex>
                           </math>
					                   </para.body>
                     </para>
				              </li>
				              <li>
					                <para>
                        <para.body>
						                     <math>
                              <latex>U(0,0)</latex>
                           </math> as the tail point of an arrow representing <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                           </math>, the tip of this arrow will be at <math>
                              <latex>V(3,-1)</latex>
                           </math>
					                   </para.body>
                     </para>
				              </li>
			            </ul>
		          </answer.showme.block.body>
         </answer.showme.block>
      </answer.showme>
	  </showme>
</showme.pack>
